{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01NdgstufnLmdB2vqB8xsGMe","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Detailed Findings:\n\n1. Resource Files Analysis:\n   - Consistently use Jakarta framework annotations\n   - Dependency injection with `@Inject`\n   - Transactional methods with `@Transactional`\n   - REST endpoint routing with `@Path`, `@GET`, `@POST`\n   - Validation with `@Valid` and `@NotNull`\n   - Security annotations like `@RolesAllowed`\n\n2. Domain Features:\n   - Mostly interfaces defining domain operations\n   - No direct CDI annotations in the feature interfaces\n   - Likely implemented with CDI in other classes\n\n3. EntityUtils:\n   - `@ApplicationScoped` annotation present\n   - Uses Lombok `@AllArgsConstructor`\n   - Converts JPA entities to domain models\n\n4. Domain Model Providers:\n   - Simple interfaces like `HashProvider`\n   - No CDI annotations in these interfaces\n\n5. Quarkus/Smallrye Imports:\n   - Interestingly, no direct imports from `io.quarkus` or `io.smallrye` were found\n   - The project uses Jakarta EE standards instead of specific Quarkus annotations\n\nNotable Observations:\n- Heavy use of Jakarta EE standards\n- Dependency Injection primarily through `@Inject`\n- Transactional support with standard Jakarta annotations\n- Clean separation between web, domain, and infrastructure layers\n\nWould you like me to dive deeper into any specific aspect of these findings?"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d45be86e-3e5a-4433-b76a-a33ae6e615f7","uuid":"5affcaa3-94ae-4116-9a9f-e4680d6cf2e9"}
