{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_012J6k5kK6Scs2SSDebRxACL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I see `RESTEASY002225: Deploying jakarta.ws.rs.core.Application: class org.example.realworldapi.RestApplication` but no specific resource registrations logged. The issue is that RESTEasy-CDI auto-discovery isn't finding our resource classes. In the previous iteration, when `getClasses()` was used, RESTEasy created the instances itself (without CDI). Now with auto-discovery, RESTEasy needs to find `@Path` annotated classes.\n\nThe problem is that RESTEasy's CDI integration needs to scan for classes, but in an embedded (non-servlet) context, RESTEasy might not have a way to auto-discover resources. The solution is to add `getClasses()` back BUT have RESTEasy resolve instances through CDI. With RESTEasy-CDI, even when `getClasses()` returns classes, the CDI extension should intercept instantiation.\n\nLet me try a different approach: register resources in `getClasses()` and rely on RESTEasy-CDI to inject them properly. The key issue before was that `getClasses()` prevented CDI injection. But that was because the resources didn't have `@RequestScoped`. Now they do. With RESTEasy-CDI on the classpath, if the resource classes are CDI beans (which they are with `@RequestScoped`), RESTEasy should get them from CDI."}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1360,"cache_read_input_tokens":71944,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1360,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":541},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d45be86e-3e5a-4433-b76a-a33ae6e615f7","uuid":"f5240665-2353-4c5c-afd9-ca2e29dd2850"}
